Although it is widely recognized that the United States has a severe and broad&amp;amp;nbsp;systemic racism problem, recent events have dramatically elevated the issue.&amp;amp;nbsp;Widespread protests in the US and around the world have brought much-deserved&amp;amp;nbsp;attention to the plights of Blacks, Indigenous and People of Color (BIPOC)&amp;amp;nbsp;regarding injustices that they experience on a daily basis. For the sake not only&amp;amp;nbsp;of BIPOC, but communities and societies as a whole, racial injustice can no longer&amp;amp;nbsp;be ignored or minimalized.1
